The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 A Cossipore Gun and Shell Factory employee immolated himself on the factory premises at 9.40 am on Friday. Bablu Hazra, 48, was rushed to the factory hospital, where he was pronounced dead. In the absence of a suicide note, police have initiated a case of unnatural death. Hazra was a resident of Mall Road, Dum Dum. 

 An automatic platform ticket-vending machine was installed at Howrah station?s new complex on Thursday by R.R. Bhandari, South Eastern Railway general manager. Coins of Re 1 and Rs 5 denomination will have to be inserted into the machine. Officials said suburban tickets, too, will be made available through the machine in future. Chief operations manager Partha Sengupta, chief commercial manager Somnath Mukherjee and divisional railway manager (Kharagpur) Sakeel Ahmed were present at the function. 

 Sri Dharmasaastha Bhajana Samithy will celebrate its 8th mandala puja on Saturday and Sunday at Shiv-Kali temple on Fakirpara Road in Behala.

 An exhibition of handicrafts made by the physically-challenged was opened by fire services minister Pratim Chatterjee at Diamond Park, near Thakurpukur, on Thursday, to mark International Day for the Disabled. 

 A march organised by Action Aid India and the Disability Activists Forum was flagged off from the Fountain of Joy, near Victoria Memorial, at 9.30 am on Friday and ended at Shahid Minar. Around 300 people from the city and its adjoining districts participated. An Action Aid India spokesperson said the organisers wanted to highlight the rights of the challenged. 

 Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee will inaugurate a four-day programme to protest terrorism, at Rabindra Sadan from December 9. Nandita Das, Javed Akhtar, Alyque Padamsee, Teesta Setalvad, Sunil Gangopadhyay and Soumitra Chatterjee are among those who will take part in the programme, organised by Spandan. Representatives from Bangladesh, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Germany and Syria have confirmed their participation.

 Veteran screen and stage actor Ajit Bandopadhyay died in a city nursing home on Friday after a protracted illness. He was 94. Bandopadhyay, who entered the film industry in 1946, became famous after his lead role in Santi and Pratima. Among his other films are Krishnakanter Will, Michael Madhusudan, Uttar Falguni, and Satyajit Ray?s Sakha Prasakha and Agantuk. As a stage actor, he was known for his performances in Nabanna, Ulka and Shyamali. 

